\cf0 \ul 1. Global statistical comparison of BachBot\'92s output with repertoire \'91archetypes\'92.\ulnone \
\
Common practice, Classical music tends to exhibit regular hierarchical structures in several parameters including the overall usage of metrical positions (which relate to the metre) and pitches (which reflect the key). We can use these as a metric, but they're obviously rather crude.\
\
There is also often a big difference between the kind of information contained in one work and that of general practice so a consideration of variance would need to be built in. For instance, compare the position usage in Fugue no.5 (\'91Fugue-5.png\'92) with its distinctive dotted rhythm from the wider collection of fugues (\'91Fugues.png\'92). This division is much less pronounced in the chorales than most repertoires (both in terms of pitch and rhythm), so it\'92s possible that we won\'92t be too troubled by it for that dataset.\
\
Examples:\
\ul a. Metrical position usage\ulnone \
Chorales (individually and collectively) have a distinctive metrical profile which differs in clear ways from wider practice. See the difference between the histograms for Bach chorales (\'91Bach-chorales.png\'92) as compared with those for Bach fugues, for instance. I\'92ve also uploaded some code for extracting this information (\'91Beat-count-4.py\'92 and \'91Chorale-Beat-Count.py\'92) and can add other examples if needed. This should help with engaging with music21, extracting pieces in a certain key signature, etc etc.\
